# Coding Style Rules

## General Principles

- Prefer concise, readable code over verbose explanations
- Eliminate unnecessary intermediate variables when the logic can be expressed inline
- Use elegant fallbacks and default values
- Consolidate related logic into single expressions when it improves readability

## JavaScript/TypeScript Patterns

### Variable Elimination

- Remove intermediate variables when the value is only used once
- Prefer inline expressions over separate variable declarations
- Example: Use `new Date().getTimezoneOffset()` directly in API calls instead of storing in a variable

### Conditional Logic Simplification

- Consolidate multi-line conditional logic into single expressions when possible
- Use logical operators (`||`, `&&`) for elegant fallbacks
- Example: `req.body.election_title || new Date(Date.now() - (req.body.timezone_offset || 0) * 60_000).toString().slice(0, 21)`

### Default Values and Fallbacks

- Use `|| 0` or similar patterns for clean default value handling
- Prefer inline fallbacks over separate conditional blocks
- Example: `(req.body.timezone_offset || 0)` instead of checking if undefined

### Mathematical Expressions

- Use underscores in large numbers for readability (e.g., `60_000` instead of `60000`)
- Prefer direct calculations over intermediate steps when the logic is clear

## Code Structure Preferences

### API Endpoints

- Keep request body destructuring minimal
- Handle optional parameters with inline fallbacks
- Prefer single-line expressions for simple transformations

### React Components

- Eliminate unnecessary state variables when values can be computed inline
- Use direct function calls in event handlers when the logic is simple
- Prefer concise prop passing over intermediate variables

## Readability Guidelines

- When a single expression can replace multiple lines of conditional logic, prefer the single expression
- Use descriptive variable names, but don't create variables just for the sake of naming
- Balance conciseness with clarity - if an inline expression becomes too complex, break it out

### Comments

- Avoid comments that simply restate what each line of code does
- Prefer comments that explain intent, trade-offs, constraints, or layout/section structure
- Short JSX block comments that mark logical sections (e.g. `{/* Title */}`, `{/* Description */}`) are acceptable when they make it easier to scan or safely collapse regions in large components

## Anti-Patterns to Avoid

- Creating variables that are only used once
- Multi-line conditional blocks that can be expressed as single expressions
- Unnecessary intermediate steps in simple calculations
- Verbose fallback handling when logical operators can handle it elegantly
